  "local_port": 57606,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to get an admission at Oxford University?",
  "response": "Gaining admission to the University of Oxford is a competitive and multi-step process. Below is a general outline of the procedure:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Choose a Course**\n   - Oxford offers a wide range of undergraduate and postgraduate courses. Research and select the course you want to study.\n   - Check the specific entry requirements for your chosen course on the [University of Oxford website](https://www.ox.ac.uk/).\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Check Entry Requirements**\n   - **Undergraduate**: Typically requires excellent grades in high school qualifications (e.g., A-levels, IB, AP, or equivalent).\n   - **Postgraduate**: Requires a strong undergraduate degree (usually a First or Upper Second Class Honours) in a related field.\n   - English language proficiency (e.g., IELTS, TOEFL) if English is not your first language.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Prepare Your Application**\n   - **Undergraduate**:\n     - Apply through UCAS (Universities and Colleges Admissions Service) by the **October 15** deadline (for most courses).\n     - Write a personal statement highlighting your academic interests, achievements, and suitability for the course.\n     - Provide predicted grades from your school.\n   - **Postgraduate**:\n     - Apply through the University of Oxford\u2019s graduate application portal by the specified deadline (varies by course).\n     - Submit a statement of purpose, CV, academic transcripts, and references.\n\n---\n\n### 4. **Submit Additional Materials**\n   - Some courses require additional materials, such as:\n     - Written work (e.g., essays or research papers).\n     - Admissions tests (e.g., BMAT for Medicine, LNAT for Law, MAT for Mathematics).\n     - Check the specific requirements for your course.\n\n---\n\n### 5. **Attend an Interview**\n   - Shortlisted candidates are invited for interviews, which usually take place in December (undergraduate) or during the admissions cycle (postgraduate).\n   - Interviews are designed to assess your academic potential, critical thinking, and suitability for the course.\n\n---\n\n### 6. **Await the Decision**\n   - Undergraduate offers are typically released in January.\n   - Postgraduate decisions are communicated within the time frame specified by the department.\n\n---\n\n### 7. **Meet Conditions of Offer**\n   - If you receive a conditional offer, you must meet the specified conditions (e.g., achieving certain grades in exams).\n   - Once you fulfill the conditions, your place is confirmed.\n\n---\n\n### 8. **Apply for Funding**\n   - Explore scholarships, bursaries, and other funding opportunities offered by Oxford or external organizations.\n\n---\n\n### 9. **Prepare for Enrollment**\n   - Once your place is confirmed, complete the enrollment process, including visa applications (if applicable) and accommodation arrangements.\n\n---\n\n### Key Tips:\n   - Start preparing early, especially for admissions tests and interviews.\n   - Tailor your application to demonstrate your passion for the subject and your academic abilities.\n   - Seek guidance from teachers, mentors, or Oxford\u2019s admissions resources.\n\nFor detailed and course-specific information, visit the [University of Oxford Admissions website](https://www.ox.ac.uk/admissions).",
  "temperature": 1.0,
